 Danielle Allen untangles the US government’s COVID-19 victories and failures to offer a plan for creating a more resilient democratic polity—one that can better respond to both the present pandemic and future crises. Looking to history, Allen also identifies the challenges faced by democracies in other times that required strong government action. In an analysis spanning from ancient Greece to the Reconstruction Amendments and the present day, Allen argues for the relative effectiveness of collaborative federalism over authoritarian compulsion and for the unifying power of a common cause. But for democracy to endure, we—as participatory citizens—must commit to that cause: a just and equal social contract and support for good governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aCrisis management in governmentzUnited States. 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ademocracy, democratic, government, governing, politics, political science, coronavirus, pandemic, covid-19, vaccines, outbreaks, tracing, contact, masking, masks, disease, strong action, response, united states of america, american society, crisis management, collaborative federalism, federal, common cause, unity, good governance, 21st century, president, executive, congress, representatives, senators, senate, officials, leadership, peace.1 aLear, Jonathan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226815619423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226815619/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles